[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] The path of a request through your application.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] The following JSON examples do not represent a specific format, and especially not OTLP/JSON, which is more verbose.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This is the root span, denoting the beginning and end of the entire operation.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Note that it has a `trace_id` field indicating the trace, but has no `parent_id`.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This span encapsulates specific tasks, like saying greetings, and its parent is the `hello` span.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Note that it shares the same `trace_id` as the root span, indicating it’s a part of the same trace.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Additionally, it has a `parent_id` that matches the `span_id` of the `hello` span.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This span represents the third operation in this trace and, like the previous one, it’s a child of the `hello` span.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] That also makes it a sibling of the `hello-greetings` span.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] These three blocks of JSON all share the same `trace_id`, and the `parent_id` field represents a hierarchy.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Another thing you’ll note is that each Span looks like a structured log.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] One way to think of Traces is that they’re a collection of structured logs with context, correlation, hierarchy, and more baked in.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] However, these “structured logs” can come from different processes, services, VMs, data centers, and so on.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This is what allows tracing to represent an end-to-end view of any system.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] To understand how tracing in OpenTelemetry works, let’s look at a list of components that will play a part in instrumenting our code.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A Tracer Provider (sometimes called `TracerProvider`) is a factory for `Tracer`s.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] In most applications, a Tracer Provider is initialized once and its lifecycle matches the application’s lifecycle.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Tracer Provider initialization also includes Resource and Exporter initialization.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] It is typically the first step in tracing with OpenTelemetry.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] In some language SDKs, a global Tracer Provider is already initialized for you.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A Tracer creates spans containing more information about what is happening for a given operation, such as a request in a service.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Tracers are created from Tracer Providers.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Trace Exporters send traces to a consumer.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This consumer can be standard output for debugging and development-time, the OpenTelemetry Collector, or any open source or vendor backend of your choice.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Context Propagation is the core concept that enables Distributed Tracing.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] With Context Propagation, Spans can be correlated with each other and assembled into a trace, regardless of where Spans are generated.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] To learn more about this topic, see the concept page on Context Propagation.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A **span** represents a unit of work or operation.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Spans are the building blocks of Traces.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Spans can be nested, as is implied by the presence of a parent span ID: child spans represent sub-operations.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This allows spans to more accurately capture the work done in an application.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Span context is the part of a span that is serialized and propagated alongside Distributed Context and Baggage.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Because Span Context contains the Trace ID, it is used when creating Span Links.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Attributes are key-value pairs that contain metadata that you can use to annotate a Span to carry information about the operation it is tracking.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For example, if a span tracks an operation that adds an item to a user’s shopping cart in an eCommerce system, you can capture the user’s ID, the ID of the item to add to the cart, and the cart ID.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] You can add attributes to spans during or after span creation.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Prefer adding attributes at span creation to make the attributes available to SDK sampling.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] If you have to add a value after span creation, update the span with the value.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Additionally, there are Semantic Attributes, which are known naming conventions for metadata that is typically present in common operations.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] It’s helpful to use semantic attribute naming wherever possible so that common kinds of metadata are standardized across systems.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A Span Event can be thought of as a structured log message (or annotation) on a Span, typically used to denote a meaningful, singular point in time during the Span’s duration.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A Span is best used to track the first scenario because it’s an operation with a start and an end.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A Span Event is best used to track the second scenario because it represents a meaningful, singular point in time.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Since span events also contain attributes, the question of when to use events instead of attributes might not always have an obvious answer.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] To inform your decision, consider whether a specific timestamp is meaningful.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For example, when you’re tracking an operation with a span and the operation completes, you might want to add data from the operation to your telemetry.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Links exist so that you can associate one span with one or more spans, implying a causal relationship.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For example, let’s say we have a distributed system where some operations are tracked by a trace.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] In response to some of these operations, an additional operation is queued to be executed, but its execution is asynchronous.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] We can track this subsequent operation with a trace as well.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] We would like to associate the trace for the subsequent operations with the first trace, but we cannot predict when the subsequent operations will start.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] We need to associate these two traces, so we will use a span link.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] You can link the last span from the first trace to the first span in the second trace.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Now, they are causally associated with one another.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Links are optional but serve as a good way to associate trace spans with one another.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A span status that is `Unset` means that the operation it tracked successfully completed without an error.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] When a span status is `Error`, then that means some error occurred in the operation it tracks.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For example, this could be due to an HTTP 500 error on a server handling a request.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] When a span status is `Ok`, then that means the span was explicitly marked as error-free by the developer of an application.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Although this is unintuitive, it’s not required to set a span status as `Ok` when a span is known to have completed without error, as this is covered by `Unset`.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] What `Ok` does is represent an unambiguous “final call” on the status of a span that has been explicitly set by a user.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This is helpful in any situation where a developer wishes for there to be no other interpretation of a span other than “successful”.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] To reiterate: `Unset` represents a span that completed without an error.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] `Ok` represents when a developer explicitly marks a span as successful.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] In most cases, it is not necessary to explicitly mark a span as `Ok`.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] When a span is created, it is one of `Client`, `Server`, `Internal`, `Producer`, or `Consumer`.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] This span kind provides a hint to the tracing backend as to how the trace should be assembled.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] According to the OpenTelemetry specification, the parent of a server span is often a remote client span, and the child of a client span is usually a server span.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Similarly, the parent of a consumer span is always a producer and the child of a producer span is always a consumer.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] If not provided, the span kind is assumed to be internal.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For more information regarding SpanKind, see SpanKind.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A client span represents a synchronous outgoing remote call such as an outgoing HTTP request or database call.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Note that in this context, “synchronous” does not refer to `async/await`, but to the fact that it is not queued for later processing.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] A server span represents a synchronous incoming remote call such as an incoming HTTP request or remote procedure call.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Internal spans represent operations which do not cross a process boundary.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Things like instrumenting a function call or an Express middleware may use internal spans.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Producer spans represent the creation of a job which may be asynchronously processed later.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] It may be a remote job such as one inserted into a job queue or a local job handled by an event listener.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] Consumer spans represent the processing of a job created by a producer and may start long after the producer span has already ended.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/signals-traces] For more information, see the traces specification.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:distributed-tracing-deep/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
